Imo State Governor Hope Uzodimma enjoined Muslims to take seriously the message of Prophet Mohammed that finds expression in peace, unity, love, sacrifice and fear of God in all their undertakings. He reminded them that Nigeria craves for their prayers today in the face of security challenges and other problems threatening the unity, peace, love and progress of the country, noting that all the faiths owe the country and her leadership a duty to ensure that she lives up to her everyone’s expectations. “Without peace and unity, there is not much that can be achieved by our dear country. So, it behoves on all us to work towards the peace, unity and love that will propel the country’s progress and development.”   Abiodun preaches against immorality, get-rich syndrome     IG orders security at prayer grounds, others     Sanwo-Olu, Obasa urge peaceful co-existence, spirituality   Cross River State Governor Prof. Ben Ayade has urged the Muslim faithful to imbibe the teachings of the Prophet Muhammed on the essence of the religious obligation, insisting that ‘this is the time, more than ever before, to connect to the virtue of love, compassion, unity and generosity which Prophet Muhammed symbolises and which the holy month of Ramadan taught us’. Ayade appealed to the Muslim Ummah to shun divisive tendencies capable of drawing back the country’s wheel of progress and development. He urged them to be law-abiding and continue to pray for a peaceful Nigeria.